#correct time columns by converting string format into datetime format:

#correct user_type, member_gender, and bike_share_for_all_trip columns format by converting string into category:
category_var_dict = {'user_type': ['Customer', 'Subscriber'],
                    'member_gender': ['Male', 'Female', 'Other'],
                    'bike_share_for_all_trip': ['Yes', 'No']}

for var in category_var_dict:
    category_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = category_var_dict[var])
    df[var] = df[var].astype(category_var)

Structure of the dataset¶

We have 183215 bike-lending records, which spans 28 days of February in 2019, in our dataset after preliminary cleaning, and 5 variables are categorical and 11 variables are numeric. Some columns that have unproper formats have been corrected. The structure is very well, except for member_gender which has some missing values and we can explore univariate, bivariate and multivariate relationships between bike trip duration, start time, geo-coordinates, start and end stations, user type, gender and their age. From the users' birth year we can calculate their age.

Main feature(s) of interest in our dataset¶

The most interesting part is to identify which stations are most overwhelmed with users and expreincing low or high number of bike-returns so that more investment and bike-transportation will be channeled. Which particular bikes were overused and need some repairment. And what day hours and weekdays bike-renting is most frequent, in what geo-positions bike-sharing business is most popular. Bike-riding popularity among genders and users as well as age groups. Furthermore, we can explore which station-to-station jurneys are most lucrative.

Features in the dataset will help support our investigation into our feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect bike-lending popularity should differ in age groups, gender groups and user type groups. I also think geo-locations of stations play particular role in maping bike-lending frequency and its lucrativeness.

Univariate Exploration¶

We'll start by looking at the distribution of the bike trip durations in seconds:

# there's a long tail in the distribution, so let's put it on a log scale instead
log_binsize = 0.015
bins = 10 ** np.arange(1, np.log10(df['duration_sec'].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = df, x = 'duration_sec', bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([60, 180, 500, 5e3, 2e4, 8e4], [60, 180, 500, '5k', '20k', '80k'])
plt.xlabel('Duration (seconds)')
plt.show()

Trip duration has a long-tailed distribution, with a lot of bike trips on the short duration end, and few on the long duration end. When plotted on a log-scale, the trip duration distribution looks roughly bell-shaped, with longest durations around 500 seconds (8.3 minutes).

For age groups, in order to calculate bike trip popularity among age groups we will create another column named "age_groups" with 5 years intervals in our dataset.

In [15]:
#create age group column and plot bike trip distribution for age groups:
def spot_the_age_group(x):
    age = 2019 - x
    for i in np.arange(0, 110, 10):
        if (age >= i) and (age < i+10):
            return f'{i}s'

df['age_group'] = df['member_birth_year'].apply(spot_the_age_group)
df_age_groups = df['age_group'].value_counts().sort_index()
age_list = list(df_age_groups.index)
age_list = age_list[1:] + age_list[:1]
df_age_groups = df_age_groups.reindex(age_list)

#then we will plot the bike trip distribution among age groups
plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.bar(x=df_age_groups.index, 
        height= df_age_groups)
plt.xlabel('Age groups')
plt.show()

From that we can say that those who are in their the 20s and 30s are predominantly active in bike tripping.

Next, if we take into consideration the number of stations that bikes are inflowing and outflowing, it is worth identifying the top 20 stations in these regards respectively. In the meantime, we should probe which stations are experiecing bike deficits or proficits at the end of the period.

In [18]:
#find how many bikes each station had lended altogether
start_stations = df.start_station_id.value_counts()
start_stations = pd.DataFrame(start_stations).reset_index().rename(columns={'index':'station_id','start_station_id':'bike_outflows'})

#find how many bikes each station had received altogether
end_stations = df.end_station_id.value_counts()
end_stations = pd.DataFrame(end_stations).reset_index().rename(columns={'index':'station_id','end_station_id':'bike_inflows'})

#join the two dataframes above:
df_bike_inflow_outflow = start_stations.set_index('station_id').join(end_stations.set_index('station_id'), how='outer')
df_bike_inflow_outflow['net_bike_inflows'] = df_bike_inflow_outflow['bike_inflows'] - df_bike_inflow_outflow['bike_outflows']
df_bike_inflow_outflow.reset_index(inplace=True)

#plot the 20 receiver, lender stations as well as the top 20 stations that are experiecing bike deficits or proficits 
#at the end of the period.
sb.set_theme(style="whitegrid")
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=4, figsize = [8,8])
data1=df_bike_inflow_outflow[['station_id', 'bike_outflows']].sort_values(by=['bike_outflows'], ascending=False).head(20)
data2=df_bike_inflow_outflow[['station_id', 'bike_inflows']].sort_values(by=['bike_inflows'], ascending=False).head(20)
data3=df_bike_inflow_outflow[['station_id', 'net_bike_inflows']].sort_values(by=['net_bike_inflows'], ascending=False).head(20)
data4=df_bike_inflow_outflow[['station_id', 'net_bike_inflows']].sort_values(by=['net_bike_inflows'], ascending=True).head(20)

default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
red = sb.color_palette()[3]
sb.barplot(x="station_id", y="bike_outflows", data=data1, ax=ax[0], order=data1['station_id'], color=default_color)
sb.barplot(x="station_id", y="bike_inflows", data=data2, ax=ax[1], order=data2['station_id'], color=default_color)
sb.barplot(x="station_id", y="net_bike_inflows", data=data3, ax=ax[2], order=data3['station_id'], color=default_color)
sb.barplot(x="station_id", y="net_bike_inflows", data=data4, ax=ax[3], order=data4['station_id'], color=red)

plt.show()

From the picture above, we can say that stations 3, 6, 5, 15, 16, 21, 22, 30, 58, 67 and 81 are the top 11 stations that had most bike outflows and inflows, with 58 and 67 are championing in these regards respectively. The marketing department should pay an attention to this fact. In the meantime, the stations 67, 21, 15, 6, 44, 30, 3, 88, 182 are the top 9 stations that had stockpiled excess bikes and the stations 243, 253, 22, 71, 343, 256, 84, 81, 52 are the top 9 stations that experieced the shortage of bikes, with 67 and 243 extremelely high. Excess bikes shuold be transported to the stations falling short of enough bikes.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The trip duration variable took on a large range of values, so I looked at the data using a log transform. Under the transformation, the data looked bell-shaped, with most durations are around 500 seconds (about 8 minutes).

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

In the dataset over 200 station ids and names are missing. Rather than dropping them, I have kept them by just filling them 0s in case these rows may be inclusive for our analysis. Furthermore, for extracting the number of bike trip inflaws and outflaws per station, we have performed some join operations.

How much does the number of bikes lended for each journey (from station A to station B) vary for the whole period? This question makes a sense if we consider more investment and marketing orientation for . Here we do some job:

In [22]:
# Find the top 10 journeys lended bike numbers of which are highest for the whole period and plot a heatmap:
df_trip_flows = df[['start_station_id', 'end_station_id', 'end_station_name']].groupby(['start_station_id', 'end_station_id']).count()
df_trip_flows = df_trip_flows.reset_index().sort_values(by='end_station_name', ascending=False)
df_trip_flows.rename(columns={'end_station_name':'flow_numbers'}, inplace=True)
df_trip_flows.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
df_trip_flows.drop_duplicates(subset=['start_station_id', 'end_station_id'], inplace=True)
print(df_trip_flows.head())

columns = df_trip_flows.start_station_id.head(10)#.unique()
index = df_trip_flows.end_station_id.head(10)#.unique()
df_bike_outflows = pd.DataFrame(index=np.sort(index), columns=np.sort(columns))
df_bike_outflows

for i in df_bike_outflows.columns:
    for j in df_bike_outflows.index:
        try:
            value = df_trip_flows.head(10)[(df_trip_flows.head(10).start_station_id == i)&\
                                           (df_trip_flows.head(10).end_station_id == j)].iloc[0, 2]
        except:
            value = np.nan
        try:
            x = len(df_bike_outflows.loc[j, i])
            if x > 1:
                df_bike_outflows.loc[j, i] = [value] + (x-1)*[np.nan]
        except:
            df_bike_outflows.loc[j, i] = value
            
df_bike_outflows.fillna(0, inplace=True)
df_bike_outflows = df_bike_outflows.applymap(int)
df_bike_outflows.sort_index(inplace=True, ascending=False)

def label(x):
    if x == 0:
        return ''
    else:
        return x
labels = df_bike_outflows.applymap(label)
plt.figure(figsize = [8, 8])
sb.heatmap(df_bike_outflows, annot = labels, fmt = '',
           cmap = 'vlag_r', center = 0)
plt.xlabel('start_station_id', labelpad=20)
plt.ylabel('end_station_id', labelpad=20)
plt.show()

From that picture we can say that overall trip durations per day fluctuated and peaked at the end of the period.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The stations are located like particular clusters in four major areas. The first two biggest pair are quite closer to each other. The service volumes in hours per receiver station varies across the stations. Bike trip activeness alse varies tremendously across genders, user type and age groups, being men, subscribers and the youth (20s and 30s) predominant respectfully. And service volumes in hours per day fluctuates across the whole period.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Interestingly, the overall volume of bike trip durations peaked at the end of the month, which is crucial for resource planning orientation!

# identifying the statuse of each station 
df_map = df_bike_inflow_outflow.join(df_geo_locations.set_index('start_station_id'), on='station_id')
df_map = df_map[df_map.station_id != 0]
def status(x):
    if x > 0:
        return 'excess'
    elif x < 0:
        return 'shortage'
    else:
        return 'balanced'
    
df_map['station_status'] = df_map['net_bike_inflows'].apply(status)
df_map['net_bike_inflows'] = df_map['net_bike_inflows'].apply(abs)
print(df_map.head())

def label_point(x, y, val, ax):
    a = pd.concat({'x': x, 'y': y, 'val': val}, axis=1)
    for i, point in a.iterrows():
        ax.text(point['x'], point['y'], int(point['val']))

hue_order = ["excess", "shortage", "balanced"]
